WHAT MAKES THE GYM BUSY AND WHEN TO AVOID IT

Project Motivation

Going to the gym is a regular part of my routine, but I’ve always wondered: when is it most crowded? And is there any pattern to how busy the gym gets? I wanted to track and analyse this so I could plan my workouts more efficiently and avoid peak times. The data came from a personal log collected via Google Forms every time I went to the gym.

Data Collection

Data was manually entered into a Google Form after each gym session. The form recorded the time, day, how busy the gym felt, how many people were using benches and squat racks, and my satisfaction. It was exported into a Google Sheet, then loaded into R for analysis and visualisation.

Variables Explored

  • Day of the week
  • Hour of the day
  • Bench vs squat rack usage
  • Overall gym busyness rating (1–5)
  • User satisfaction (when available)

Gym Busyness by Day

The gym tends to be busiest mid-week. Tuesday and Wednesday show the highest average busyness ratings, while weekends are quieter. This plot helps identify which days to avoid if you prefer a less crowded workout.

Hourly Busyness Trends

Gym usage follows a clear pattern: early morning (6–8am) and late afternoon to evening (4–7pm) are peak hours. Late mornings and mid-afternoons are generally quieter, which is valuable for scheduling sessions during off-peak times.

Bench vs Squat Rack Usage

This scatterplot compares how often people use benches vs squat racks. While there’s some variability, there’s no clear trade-off — some sessions have both in use, others neither. It highlights how demand can vary without a fixed pattern.

Combined Time and Day Busyness

This heatmap shows the interaction between the day of the week and the hour of the day. Peak busyness clusters on weekday evenings. Early mornings are also busy on weekdays. This is the most useful visual for finding the least crowded gym windows.

Bench and Squat Usage Distribution

The density plots show benches are slightly more commonly used than squat racks. The shapes of the curves also help reveal typical usage counts — around 2–4 users at any given time.

Gym Satisfaction Distribution (If Available)

Where available, satisfaction scores show most sessions were positive (scores 4–5). Fewer entries exist for negative experiences, suggesting a possible bias toward logging only more satisfying gym visits.

Wrapping Up: Final Insights

To summarise:

  • Avoid the gym on weekday evenings and Tuesday–Wednesday if you dislike crowds.
  • Mid-morning and mid-afternoon are quieter times to train.
  • There’s no strong pattern between bench and squat usage — demand varies.
  • Most workouts were rated as satisfying, but more negative examples would improve understanding.

This analysis helps optimise gym visits for comfort and efficiency. More detailed tracking over time would strengthen these findings.
